# AlphaSwarm Worker Agent Model
# Register with: ollama create alphaswarm-worker -f modelfiles/Modelfile.worker
#
# Base: qwen3.6:35b-a3b-nvfp4 (36B MoE ~3B active, MLX format) — model
# decision 2026-06-11, benchmarked on this M1 Max 64GB (ollama 0.30.7):
#   qwen3:8b (old, GGUF/llama.cpp):     prefill  422 t/s, decode 43 t/s
#   qwen3.5:35b (GGUF/llama.cpp):       prefill  833 t/s, decode 60 t/s
#   qwen3.6:35b-a3b-nvfp4 (MLX, THIS):  prefill 2361 t/s, decode 56 t/s
# 2.8x prefill over the GGUF MoE path matters because persona prompts are
# ~2.5k tokens vs ~150 output tokens. Newest-generation MoE on top.
#
# Requirements: OLLAMA_USE_MLX=1 (scripts/configure_ollama_app_env.sh sets
# it + persists via LaunchAgent) and >=32GB unified memory — otherwise
# ollama SILENTLY falls back to llama.cpp. Verify after a cold start:
#   grep "MLX engine initialized" ~/.ollama/logs/server.log
# Note: nvfp4 variants are text-only (no vision) — fine for the swarm.
# Dense-parallel-decode is bandwidth-capped on M1 Max, so a fast-MoE
# single stream beats parallel dense 8B; NUM_PARALLEL=4 stays for prefill
# overlap on other archs.
FROM qwen3.6:35b-a3b-nvfp4
PARAMETER num_ctx 4096
PARAMETER temperature 0.7
PARAMETER num_gpu 999
# Decision JSON is ~100-150 tokens; 400 caps pathological repetition loops
# (the 14-20 min/call tail observed in the 41.3 smoke) at zero quality cost.
# Re-register after editing: ollama create alphaswarm-worker -f modelfiles/Modelfile.worker
PARAMETER num_predict 400
